For the safety of all of our students, parents, guardians, staff members, and our community, the decision has been made to close all school sites in the Cascade Union Elementary School District starting Tuesday, March 17. Please share. Thank you.

post_text:
This message is to inform you that the Cascade Union Elementary Schools will continue to operate normally tomorrow.
Superintendent Provence will be attending two meetings tomorrow that will explain the governor’s latest message, directives from the California Department of Education and the Shasta county superintendent of schools, and determine next steps if the need for holding school in an alternate manner is necessary.
All non-essential activities such as sports activities and concerts have been canceled here and across the county. Please continue to monitor the CUESD website (CUESD.com) or the CUESD App.
Additional updates will be provided as they become available using the same means as you are receiving this message.
Please continue to follow protocols sent previously, and remind your children of the importance of practicing good hygiene.
Thank you for your attentiveness to this and all messages.

Jason Provence, Superintendent

post_text: THE CASCADE UNION ELEMENTARY SCHOOL DISTRICT WILL BE CLOSED ON WEDNESDAY, OCTOBER 9 AND THURSDAY, OCTOBER 10 DUE TO THE EXPECTED POWER OUTAGE. WE HOPE TO BE ABLE TO RESUME THE REGULAR SCHOOL SCHEDULE ON FRIDAY, OCTOBER 11, BUT THIS REMAINS UNCERTAIN AT THIS TIME. Stay tuned to local radio/TV stations for additional information. We will be sending messages to the phone on file for you, but without power, it is unclear whether or not you will receive these messages. District land lines and email will not be available during this time, but we will be sending out further notifications through Blackboard.

Thank you Brittney for your relentless endeavors to make our students the best they can be!

post_text:
A BIG WIN FOR Cascade District School ANDERSON HEIGHTS!

On Saturday, March 2, 2019 the Gifted and Talented students (GATE) from Anderson Heights competed in the Creative Competitions Program called Odyssey of the Mind. The California North Association Regional Competition was held at Mt. View School in Redding and was open to all North State GATE Teams. Team “Shining Stars’ comprised of Sophia, Alison, Melina, Carly, Ayvin, and Tyler placed first in the Division I section where they acted out an original skit in front of an original backdrop wearing original costumes. The program promotes creativity by challenging teams to solve divergent problems with more than one solution. The participants learn teamwork, the appreciation and understanding of others, and that a group is a more powerful thinking force than an individual. They develop a sense of self-respect for others through preparatory activities such a brainstorming and role-playing. All work must be done by team members only. A big Congratulations to Anderson Heights Shining Stars.

shared_text:
Judy Flores
November 27, 2017 at 7:08 PM ·

This morning, I was welcomed to the schools in the Cascade Union Elementary School District by Superintendent Jason Provence. We were able to visit classrooms at each school, including the Learning Center at Meadow Lane, the Interactive STEAM Room and the 4th-grade classroom of Mrs. Quibell at Anderson Heights, and 8th-grade students in both Honors Math with Ms. McLean and goal setting with Ms. Morey at Anderson Middle School. It is great to see all they are working on to build a common language of expectations and the positive impact it is having on their environment. It was great to learn about all the opportunities students have that are enriching their school experience!
